The paper proposes a method for estimating global pairwise interaction effects using Bayesian neural networks. This involves modelling the relationship between input features and output using a BNN, which is a common approach in machine learning and falls under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the use of Hessian matrices to estimate interaction effects, which is a technique commonly used in optimization and falls under the category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper applies the method to real-world data involving image classification, which falls under the category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). Finally, the paper discusses the interpretability of the learned interactions, which is a topic of interest in the field of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
